# THE DEEPWATER MARCHES

*Where Strength Holds What Treaties Cannot*

A Regional Guide for Oreka — v4 — D&D 3.5e Campaign Setting

*“****The jungle does not care who planted it. The sea does not ask who**** ****drinks. And the Marches belong to whoever can hold them.****”*

## History of the Deepwater Marches

### The Giant’s Legacy & the Apelian Sea

The southwest of Oreka was shaped by water long before any Kin walked its shores. The Apelian Sea—the great southern inland mega-lake—filled a vast basin south of the Infinite Desert, its warm, sediment-rich waters fed by underground channels that the Giants themselves had carved to balance the world’s hydrology. Unlike the cold, storm-wracked Kailian Sea in the north, the Apelian is warm year-round, its shores thick with mangrove and jungle growth that drinks the lake’s moisture and exhales a perpetual green haze that clings to the canopy like a living veil. The Sea Falls connect the two mega-lakes through the body of Oreka, and in the Giant era, this waterway was the spine of continental trade—Halfling and Pekakarlik barges navigating the treacherous cascades to carry goods between north and south.

The Giants built along the Apelian’s northern shore and western rim, where the jungle thinned enough to allow their colossal architecture. Their cities here were different from the desert palaces of the interior—built of dark stone veined with green mineral, roofed with living canopy rather than cut timber, and designed to channel the warm rains that sweep in from the east every season. Rune-circles stabilized the lakeside soil against erosion and flooding, and great stone piers extended into the shallows for the barges that carried Giant-crafted goods to every corner of the world. Today those piers are submerged, their tips visible only at low water, and the rune-circles have been swallowed by root systems so ancient that the stones have become indistinguishable from the jungle floor.

### The Eke Concordant & the Southern Reach

When the Eke Concordant unified the Kin under the first two Crowned Keepers, the Deepwater Marches were the frontier—the southernmost extent of organized Kin civilization. Pasua Elves settled the great forests south and west of the Apelian, drawn by the Wind Lord’s warm currents and the old-growth canopy that reminded them of the Windweave Glade in the distant north. Halflings followed the water, establishing trading posts along the Sea Falls portage routes and building stilt-villages on the Apelian’s marshy western shore. A handful of Kovaka Elves carved stone outposts where the jungle met the mountain foothills—quiet, fortified places that watched the deep forest with the same grim vigilance they brought to every border they held.

The Eke Concordant era saw perhaps a dozen small settlements flourish around the Apelian, but even at its height, the Marches were never densely populated. The jungle was too thick, the terrain too difficult, and the distance from the northern centers of power too great. What settlements existed were self-reliant—Pasua villages that traded internally, Halfling boatwrights who maintained the portage routes, and Kovaka watchtowers that sent reports northward but rarely received instructions in return. The Marches were governed by distance and necessity, and the Kin who lived there learned early that their survival depended on their own strength and the strength of their neighbors.

### The Shattering of Man

When the Third Crowned Keeper’s failure shattered the Eke Concordant, the Deepwater Marches felt the collapse as abandonment rather than destruction. There were no Taraf-Imro warlords here, no Eruskan harbors to blockade, no Orean quarries to dispute. The trade routes simply stopped. The Pekakarlik barges that had carried news, tools, and grain from the north ceased their runs. The portage stations were unmanned. The Pasua villages and Halfling stilt-towns, accustomed to self-reliance, adjusted—but the adjustment was permanent. The Marches became what they had always threatened to become: a land cut off from the world above the desert, answerable to no authority, sustained by whatever the jungle and the lake could provide.

This isolation proved both shield and curse. The Marches were too remote to attract the factional violence that scarred the Kinsweave, and too poor in strategic resources to draw the ambitions of petty kings. But isolation also meant stagnation. Without trade, the settlements shrank. Without governance, disputes were settled by strength or by the slow, patient diplomacy of Pasua bards who had no one to appeal to but each other. The great forests grew thicker, the Giant ruins sank deeper, and the Marches settled into a quiet, stubborn survival that would define the region’s character for centuries to come.

### The Deceivers’ War & the Dark Dawn

The Deceivers’ arrival through the Silence Breach in the far southeast sent shockwaves across southern Oreka, but it was the aftermath—not the invasion itself—that transformed the Deepwater Marches forever. The Deceiver host marched north through the Eternal Steppe and into the Infinite Desert, bypassing the Marches entirely. The Kin of the south, led by the Pasua and Mytrone elite warriors called the Far Riders, pursued the invaders and brought them to battle on the Steppe in the engagement known as the Battle of Dark Dawn.

The battle itself was a tactical victory for the Kin—but it was bought at catastrophic cost. The combined toll of the Running War and Dark Dawn left only one warrior in ten standing from the forces who had ridden south at the Brotherhood’s call. It was a victory that sowed a hundred future wars. When the Deceiver captains ordered the deliberate scatter, hundreds of warbands fled in every direction, plunging into the fires they had set themselves. Many headed west and southwest, into the deep jungles around the Apelian Sea. They brought with them the tools of their failed invasion: goblin servitor-troops, war-wargs trained for cavalry and ambush, hobgoblin officers, and the alien equipment of an army designed to conquer a world. What they found in the Marches was exactly what they needed: dense terrain that favored concealment, warm climate that sustained year-round operations, and a Kin population too small and scattered to mount effective resistance.

The goblins and wargs, however, were not content to remain tools. The chaos of Dark Dawn had cracked the chains of Deceiver command, and in the years that followed, tens of thousands of goblins and wargs seized their freedom. Many rebelled against their hobgoblin officers. Some joined the Kin. Others formed Free Tribes in the deep jungle, building new societies that owed nothing to the masters who had created them. The result was the most radical transformation any region of Oreka had ever undergone: within a generation, the Deepwater Marches went from a quiet Kin frontier to a contested wildland where Kin conclaves, free goblin tribes, wargbond communities, Deceiver remnants, and opportunistic predators all competed for territory around the same warm, life-giving lake.

### The Farborn Arrive

Among the forces that fled the Deceiver host was the Gilded Standard Company—a mercenary force of approximately two thousand fighting men and four thousand camp followers who had been dragged across the planes as foreign auxiliaries. They were not Kin. They were not Dómnathar. They were soldiers from another world, predominantly human with a scattering of half-orcs, half-elves, and a small cadre of foreign dwarves—hybrids and non-humans that are products of their home world’s different metaphysical rules, where mixed heritage was possible in ways that Oreka’s elemental framework does not permit (see sidebar: Farborn Humans vs. Kin Humans). When their commander, Captain Ralven Duskharrow, learned that the Dómnathar intended to use the Company as disposable shock troops, he made the decision that would define his people for three centuries: he refused.

During the scatter at Dark Dawn itself, the Company broke away in a fighting withdrawal—part of the same chaotic final engagement that ended the Running War—and fled south across the steppes, settling in the shadow of a massive solitary mountain known as the Lone Titan, near the Great Pass on the Marches’ eastern edge. The location was chosen for defense, isolation, trade access, and—though they did not understand it at the time—metaphysical protection: the Lone Titan’s deep stone roots disrupted Dómnathar scrying, making the Company invisible to the masters they had betrayed. Over three centuries, the Gilded Standard Company transformed from a refugee army into a mercenary-trader society and finally into a settled, respected non-Kin culture: the Farborn. Their population grew to approximately twenty-eight thousand, and their Titanbreed hybrid horses became the most coveted cavalry mounts on the continent.

### Sidebar: Farborn Humans vs. Kin Humans

The Farborn look human, live human lifespans, and by every physical measure *are* human—but they are not Kin. This distinction matters profoundly in Oreka.

| **Trait** | **Kin Humans** | **Farborn Humans** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Origin** | Created by a Giant and an Elf, with the Youngest Brother’s blessing | Foreign-born; arrived from another plane as Deceiver auxiliaries |
| **Elemental**** ****Attunement** | Yes — varies by culture | None at birth; emerging faintly after 300 years (the Titanbreed Paragon) |
| **Kin-Sense** | Harmonic (Kin) — race and element readable | No Registration — invisible, absent, like furniture |
| **Mixed Heritage** | Children of two Kin races are one or the other, never hybrid. No half-elves in Oreka. | Home world permitted hybrids; half-elves and half-orcs exist among original Farborn stock |
| **Apotheosis** | Eligible (if all four elements attained) | Not currently eligible — no elemental attunement |

Three centuries of intermarriage within the Farborn community have diluted the foreign bloodlines, but individuals with clearly non-Kin features still appear. These are curiosities, not scandals—the Farborn were never subject to Oreka’s metaphysical prohibition on hybrids.

### The Present Day

Today the Deepwater Marches are the most contested and least governed region in Oreka—a true frontier where power is held by strength, not by treaty. The Apelian Sea remains the region’s heart, its warm waters and fertile shores sustaining a patchwork of communities that range from established Kin cities to goblin warrens to Farborn cavalry camps. No single authority governs the Marches. The five major settlements—Tidewell, Canopy Hold, Thornwall, Titan’s Rest, and Murtavah Root—maintain fragile trade agreements and mutual defense pacts, but these accords are renegotiated constantly and enforced only by the threat of withdrawal.

The jungle itself is the region’s truest ruler. Dense, hot, and ancient, it swallows roads within a season if they are not maintained, hides entire communities in its canopy, and generates a biodiversity so extreme that the herbalists of the north consider the Marches a pharmacological paradise and a zoological nightmare in equal measure. Wargbond tribes control vast stretches of deep jungle, their mixed goblin-warg communities functioning as genuinely egalitarian societies built on mutual respect. Flamewarg cults—descendants of Gatefall Remnant cavalry who spread westward into the Marches over the centuries, drawn by the dense terrain’s suitability for fire-and-ambush tactics and the absence of any centralized authority to oppose them—haunt the transitions between jungle and steppe, and the phrase “things not Kin” carries even more weight here than in the haunted forests of the northeast.

On the region’s southern rim, a tower of dark stone rises from a rocky spur extending into the Apelian Sea. This is the Dómnathar stronghold in the Deepwater Marches—quietly rebuilt over 300 years from the Deceiver remnant core that fled here after Dark Dawn. Nearby, the settlement known as the Deceiver’s Refuge teaches a forbidden art—the Deceiver’s Feat, which allows its practitioner to conceal their Kin-sense signature, rendering them invisible to the elemental resonance that defines every living being in Oreka. Whether this is a tool of survival or a weapon of infiltration depends entirely on who is asking.

The region’s total population across its recognized settlements stands at roughly 42,000 souls—but this figure accounts only for the Kin and Farborn who live in established communities. The goblin and warg populations of the deep jungle are uncounted and likely exceed the settled population by a significant margin. The Deepwater Marches are not empty. They are simply ungoverned—and that is precisely what makes them dangerous.

## Landscape & Named Landmarks

The Deepwater Marches occupy the southwest of Oreka, wrapped around the Apelian Sea and bounded by the Infinite Desert to the north, the Eternal Steppe to the east, and the mountain spurs of the Giant’s Teeth to the northeast. The terrain is overwhelmingly forested—dense tropical and subtropical jungle that thrives on the Apelian’s moisture, giving way to lighter woodland and scrub on the steppe transitions. The climate is warm year-round (80–95°F), humid near the lake, and marked by a wet season of torrential rains that turns every path to mud and every stream to a torrent.

### The Apelian Sea

The great southern freshwater mega-lake, warm and sediment-rich, its waters a deep blue-green clouded by mineral runoff from the surrounding jungle. Unlike the Kailian’s storm-battered cliffs, the Apelian’s shores are low, marshy, and thick with mangrove growth, making approach by land slow and treacherous. The lake supports an extraordinary diversity of aquatic life—massive freshwater fish, water serpents (CR 4, Swim DC 15), and luminescent eels whose glow can be seen from the shore on moonless nights. Halfling stilt-villages and Pasua canoe-stations dot the western and northern shores, connected by a network of waterways that serves as the Marches’ primary trade infrastructure.

### The Deepwood

The vast tropical jungle that blankets the land south and west of the Apelian Sea, the Deepwood is the defining terrain of the Marches. Its canopy rises 150 to 200 feet in the oldest growth, blocking sunlight so completely that the forest floor exists in permanent twilight. Wargbond tribes and Free Goblin clans control much of the interior, their knowledge of the terrain making them effectively unconquerable by conventional military force. The Deepwood is laced with Giant ruins—dark stone foundations, submerged piers, and rune-circles so overgrown that they appear to be natural rock formations until one notices the geometric precision of their edges.

### The Lone Titan

A massive solitary mountain on the Marches’ eastern edge, rising from the steppe like a clenched fist of dark stone. The Lone Titan’s deep roots disrupt Dómnathar scrying and create a metaphysical “dead zone” that shields the Farborn city of Titan’s Rest from arcane detection. The mountain’s slopes support terraced farms, hardy orchards, and the grazing lands where the Farborn’s legendary Titanbreed horses run. At the summit, a rune-circle of Giant origin still pulses with faint amber light on clear nights—the same stabilizing magic that once maintained the oasis-cities of the Infinite Desert, repurposed by three centuries of Farborn habitation into something the Giants never intended.

### The Verdant Shoals

The marshy western shore of the Apelian Sea, where the lake’s warm outflow meets the jungle’s root systems and creates a labyrinth of shallow channels, reed beds, and floating islands of matted vegetation. Halfling boatwrights navigate these waters in flat-bottomed skiffs, and the Shoals are the primary source of lake pearls, medicinal reeds, and the luminescent eel-oil that serves as the Marches’ most valuable export. Navigation requires local knowledge (Profession [Sailor] DC 15 or Knowledge [nature] DC 18), and the channels shift with every wet season.

### The Spur

A rocky peninsula extending from the Apelian’s southern shore into the lake, crowned by a tower of dark stone that is Dómnathar in origin—the hidden stronghold of the Deepwater Remnant, quietly rebuilt over 300 years since the scatter at Dark Dawn. The tower is visible from the water but difficult to approach overland—the jungle around the Spur is unnaturally dense, and Kin-sense flickers or goes dead entirely within a mile of the structure. The Deceiver’s Refuge, the settlement that teaches the forbidden Kin-sense concealment feat, sits at the base of the Spur, drawing students and fugitives from across the continent. Whether the tower and the Refuge are connected remains one of the Marches’ most dangerous open questions.

**DM NOTE:** *The Spur Tower IS the Dómnathar hidden stronghold**** ****referenced in canon. The Deepwater Remnant’s Dómnathar core has been**** ****rebuilding here for 300 years. The tower’s Kin-sense dead zone is not**** ****natural—it is generated by worked Dómnathar metal integrated into**** ****the structure’s foundations. The pre-invasion house leaders who fled**** ****here are still alive (Dómnathar lifespan: up to 1,000 years) and have**** ****personal memory of both their home world and the full 300-year**** ****rebuilding effort. The relationship between the tower and the**** ****Deceiver’s Refuge below is left to the DM—are the Refuge’s teachers**** ****unwitting cover, willing collaborators, or something else entirely?*

### The Ash Trails

A network of burned paths through the Deepwood, originally created by Flamewarg cults using fire-tactics to clear jungle corridors. Over the decades, these trails have become the closest thing the Marches have to roads—maintained by the constant passage of goblin traders, Farborn caravans, and Kin patrols. The Ash Trails are faster than cutting through virgin jungle (normal overland movement rather than half-speed) but predictable, making them prime ambush territory for hill tribe goblins and the occasional Flamewarg raiding party.

## Living Settlements

*Five established communities anchor the Deepwater Marches. None claims**** ****dominion over the others; all survive through a combination of military**** ****readiness, trade necessity, and the practical wisdom that in the**** ****Marches, your neighbor’s strength is your own.*

### Tidewell

**Population:** ~6,500

**Demographics:** 45% Halflings, 30% Pasua Elves, 15% Eruskan Humans, 10% Mixed Kin

**Leader:** Enna Farshore — Halfling, Rogue 6/Expert 3. Harbormaster; runs the trade council and Sea Falls portage rights.

**Exports:** Lake pearls, eel-oil, medicinal herbs, fish, tidal crops

**Character:** Lakeside trade hub on the Apelian’s northern shore. Stilt-market over the shallows.

*Affinity: Water (Lady of the Sea)*

*Festival: Luminous Night — floating lanterns released on the Apelian**** ****at the wet season’s end*

### Canopy Hold

**Population:** ~3,800

**Demographics:** 55% Pasua Elves, 20% Kovaka Elves, 15% Halflings, 10% Na’wasua Elves

**Leader:** Theren Deeproot — Kovaka Elf, Ranger 7/Fighter 2. Shieldfather; commands the canopy patrols and forest defense.

**Exports:** Jungle hardwoods, wind-silk, alchemical reagents, exotic feathers

**Character:** Fortified elven conclave in the western Deepwood. Platforms 120 ft up, connected by vine-bridges.

*Affinity: Air / Earth (Wind Lord / Lord of Stone)*

*Festival: Rootsong — drumming ceremony honoring the deep jungle’s**** ****spirits*

### Thornwall

**Population:** ~2,200

**Demographics:** 40% Goblins, 35% Wargs, 15% Halflings, 10% Mixed Kin

**Leader:** Kex Ironteeth (Goblin) & Silverfang (Warg) — Co-chiefs; Kex is Rogue 5/Expert 2, Silverfang is Ranger 6. Joint leadership by consensus.

**Exports:** Tinker-work, trap mechanisms, jungle guides, warg-scouted maps

**Character:** The largest Wargbond settlement in Oreka. Thorned palisade surrounding mixed warrens and den-halls.

*Kin-Sense: Breach Static (diminishing over generations as attunement**** ****develops). Three hundred years in Oreka have begun to shift the**** ****resonance of Thornwall’s oldest lineages—the wrongness is still there,**** ****but fainter, and the oldest warg elders say their grandchildren’s**** ****children will sound different still.*

*Festival: Howl Circle — communal gathering of song, story, and pack**** ****renewal under the full moon*

### Titan’s Rest

**Population:** ~28,000

**Demographics:** 90% Farborn (non-Kin humans), 5% Halflings, 3% Mixed Kin traders, 2% Other

**Leader:** Captain-General Maren Duskharrow — Farborn Human, Fighter 8/Expert 3. Elected by merit and acclamation; commands the Gilded and the Dusk Guards.

**Exports:** Titanbreed horses (8,000–15,000 gp), steppe-wool, Titansteel horseshoes, mountain herbs

**Character:** Farborn capital on the Lone Titan’s western slopes. Terraced city with cavalry fields and trade bazaar.

*Kin-Sense: No Registration — the Farborn are invisible to Kin-sense,**** ****simply absent, like furniture. Three centuries of coexistence have not**** ****changed this fundamental fact, though the emerging Titanbreed Paragon**** ****phenomenon—faint elemental resonance appearing in Farborn children**** ****raised on the Titan—suggests that the mountain’s ancient Giant**** ****rune-circle may be slowly, imperceptibly altering the Farborn’s**** ****metaphysical relationship with Oreka.*

*Festival: Founder’s Ride — annual cavalry display honoring Captain**** ****Ralven’s breakaway, with Titanborne exhibition*

### Murtavah Root

**Population:** ~1,500

**Demographics:** 35% Mixed Humans, 25% Halflings, 20% Pasua Elves, 10% Goblins, 10% Other

**Leader:** The Rootwarden — Identity obscured; rumored Pasua Elf Druid 9. Governs by counsel and quiet authority. Never seen outside the Root’s central grove.

**Exports:** Herbal remedies, jungle guides, rare fungi, information

**Character:** Secretive trade-town deep in the southern Deepwood. Part market, part refuge, part intelligence hub.

*Affinity: Air / Earth (dual patronage)*

*Festival: None publicly acknowledged — the Root keeps its own**** ****calendar*

